Part 2

The corridor had become unusually silent.

Government hospitals never become silent.

They merely change the reason for their noise.

The casualty nurse came out holding a small blood sample.

"O positive?"

she shouted towards the laboratory attendant.

He looked at the request slip.

"First testing."

"Don't assume."

She almost threw the sample into his hand.

"Run."

He disappeared.

The old NGO volunteer slowly walked towards the emergency room door.

"Can I..."

"No."

The nurse didn't even look at her.

She had probably answered the same question a hundred times that day.

The girl quietly stepped back.

A little boy, hardly eight years old, came running.

"Didi..."

He held a steel tiffin box.

"School lunch."

She smiled for the first time.

"You came alone?"

He nodded proudly.

"Cycle."

She opened the tiffin.

Four rotis.

Potato curry.

A small piece of jaggery wrapped in newspaper.

"Baba didn't eat today."

the boy said.

"He said he'll eat after telling us the crow story."

She looked towards the ICU.

"He'll tell."

The boy believed her immediately.

Children have strange faith.

Adults ask for proof.

The nurse came out again.

"Attendant."

The girl hurried.

"Blood loss is more than expected."

She simply nodded.

"We may need blood."

"I'll give."

The answer came so quickly that the nurse didn't even raise her head.

"Good."

She wrote something.

"Come."

The girl followed.

Blood bank.

A narrow room.

One old ceiling fan.

Three plastic chairs.

One weighing machine.

A calendar still showing last month.

The technician looked sleepy.

"Name?"

She answered.

He filled the form.

"Age?"

She answered.

"Weight?"

She answered.

Then...

"Any illness?"

Silence.

He looked up.

"Madam?"

She looked at the floor.

"...Yes."

"What?"

Another silence.

The nurse became impatient.

"Madam...

we don't have time."

The girl slowly raised her eyes.

"I..."

"...have AIDS."

The room became completely still.

Even the fan suddenly sounded louder.

The technician quietly kept his pen down.

The nurse stared at her.

For a second...

there was irritation.

Then guilt.

Then embarrassment.

She spoke much more softly this time.

"I'm sorry."

The girl smiled.

"It is alright."

"I asked to give blood."

"I never said I could."

Nobody spoke.

After a few seconds the technician quietly tore the half-filled form.

Without saying anything.

The girl folded her hands.

"I'm sorry."

The nurse looked away.

"No...

you don't have to be."

She left.

Outside...

two ward boys had already heard the conversation.

One whispered to another.

Within a minute...

half the corridor knew.

The same people who had stood shoulder to shoulder with her...

now unknowingly made a little space around her.

Not much.

Just enough to hurt.

She noticed.

Pretended not to.

Walked back to her chair.

Sat down.

Looked towards the ICU.

Nothing else mattered.

The little boy came running again.

"Didi."

"Can I see Baba once?"

"No."

"When?"

"When he wakes up."

The boy accepted the answer.

Children trust promises.

Adults remember excuses.

The laboratory attendant came running.

"O positive."

The nurse looked around.

"Relative?"

Nobody answered.

She shouted louder.

"Any relative of Baba?"

Silence.

The NGO girl stood up.

"He has no family."

The nurse almost lost her patience.

"What kind of life is this..."

she muttered.

Before she could finish...

someone from the crowd stepped forward.

"I'll give."

Everyone turned.

It was the flower seller.

Immediately...

the retired postman came beside him.

"My blood is also O positive."

The security guard raised his hand.

"Mine too."

The college student looked confused.

"I don't know my group...

test mine."

The auto driver spoke from behind.

"If needed...

take mine first.

He was in my auto."

The nurse looked at them.

One after another...

people kept walking forward.

A tea seller.

A tailor.

A bus conductor.

The old woman who sold jasmine flowers outside the temple.

Within two minutes...

there were fifteen people standing in a queue.

Nobody asked

"Who is he?"

Nobody asked

"What relation?"

Nobody asked

"Will someone pay?"

They simply stood there.

The laboratory technician came out.

Stopped.

Counted the queue.

Looked at the nurse.

Then smiled.

"For the first time..."

he said,

"...I have more donors than blood bags."

The nurse looked through the glass towards the unconscious old man.

She whispered almost to herself.

"Who are you, Baba?"

The answer came from somewhere behind.

A familiar voice.

Quiet.

Respectful.

"Ask anyone outside."

"They'll tell you."

"But don't ask Baba himself."

"He never tells."

The crowd slowly turned.

An old tea vendor had just arrived.

He removed his slippers before standing near the ICU door.

Folded his hands.

Closed his eyes.

And smiled...

as though he had just come to visit someone from his own family.
